Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Pour @water{300%ml} into a #saucepan{} and bring to the boil. Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the @red chilli{1/2}(halved lengthways and seeds removed), chop finely. Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(roughly chopped). Zest the @lime{1} then chop into wedges.

When the water is boiling, stir in the @star anise{1}, @salt{0.25%tsp} and add the @jasmine rice{150%g}. Bring back to the boil, then lower the heat to medium-low, pop a lid on the pan and cook for ~{10%minutes}. Remove the pan from the heat and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes}.

> The rice will continue to cook in its own steam.

Meanwhile, put a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil). Season the @duck breasts{2} on both sides with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. When hot, lay the duck breasts in the pan, skin side down. Leave to cook until the skin is golden, ~{4-5%minutes}, then turn over and brown for another ~{1%minute} on the flesh side.

Transfer the duck to a #baking tray{} (keep the frying pan with the juices!), skin side up, drizzle with the @honey{15%ml} then roast on the top shelf of your oven for ~{15%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The duck is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.
> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw duck and its packaging.

Once the duck is in the oven, finely slice the @pak choi{1}(finely sliced widthways). Chop any @portobello mushrooms{2} in half and leave the smaller ones whole. Return the frying pan with the juices to a high heat. Add the bok choy, garlic and mushrooms, stir-fry for ~{3-4%minutes}. Add a pinch of chilli, half the coriander and a pinch of lime zest. Stir in the @soy sauce{25%ml}, a squeeze of lime juice and a pinch of @sugar{} (if you have any). Remove from the heat.

When the duck is cooked, transfer to a board, cover loosely with #foil{} and leave to rest for a few mins before cutting into 5 slices. Season the veggies to taste with salt and pepper - add a squeeze more lime if it needs it. Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} (removing the star anise!) then serve in #bowls{} topped with the veggies (reheat them if necessary). Finish with the duck and a final sprinkling of coriander and chilli, if you like a kick. Enjoy!